Basiclly there are thousands of items within the game, each with its own set of stats. <br>
Say you have twenty different blades that all have the same 5str, 5hp and 5sta bonus, half of them have +5 fire resist stats, half have +5 cold stats and each of them has one unique +5 stat.<br>
Each of these stats and the item name will take up a single field within each record for each item. <br>
Thats a total of 120 fields taken up over twenty records for these twenty items.<br>
<br>
You can see the potential for a HUGE database for all the items in the game so a system called relational tables is used to cut down on storage space.<br>
<br>
In the example I used here a relational table would typicaly be split into three tables (or forms).<br>
The first would hold the item name and the unique stats, the second would hold str, sta and hp stasts and the third fire and cold stats.<br>
<br>
The first table would have to hold the item name (the unique identifier for the item) and the unique stats(taking up 40 fields) , the second table would only hold three fields for str, sta and hp as all three items have identical +5 stats for this atribute, and the third table would contain two entries one for +5 fire and one for +5 cold.<br>
<br>
This way each identical stat only has to be held on the database a single time, not multiple times. <br>
A query to the database to view the item would pick up all the unique stats in that record from the first table, be pointed to the correct record in the second table where it would pick up the stats common to all items in that record and passed to the third table where half would pick up the record for fire stas and the other half would pick up the cold stat.<br>
<br>
In this way the table size has been cut by a huge amount to 40 fields in the first table, three in the second and two in the third making a total of 45 used fields compared the the original 120.<br>
<br>
Ok, if you understand relational tables you will know that the example I just used is badly split and simplified down to a level where it wouldnt actually work so dont flame and pick it apart <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   But it does serve as an examle of how the tables would be split to reduce size.<br>
<br>
Now imagine a database with many many thousands of items in it, with between them many hundreds of thousands of stats, both unique and common to other items.<br>
Now add into that further complications of other tables for item modifiers and you begin to see what a HUGE web of links and pointers make up a database of this size, which is rationalised down as much as is possible to save on space in what is already a huge table set.<br>
<br>
Now in the last patch many items added, some were altered and new adjustable stats were added(for instance reduced AC for lower levels). Some Luclin items had no drop flags changed i believe also.<br>
This would basicly involve a rework of all the links in the database with some of them being dynamic (changable real time).<br>
When you look at it like this, making a change on an item at the top level or adjusting a poiinter real time could potentialy cause a domino like effect across tables and affect items in an unexpected way or even alter items that are apparantly un connected because they use the same tables where a change has been made.<br>
<br>
Bearing in mind that some items had no drop flags changed it is very possible that had a domino effect and caused the no rent flags to be dropped from the PoA keys.<br>
<br>
Im not saying this DID happen, Im just trying to show that it IS possible that an unintended change was caused this way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzyphyr.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zyphyr</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 291<br> <font color=#333333>(5/25/02 12:09:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1168.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Airplane changed?</span><hr size=1> Bahter - there is absolutely no reason to believe that that is how they have thing set up.<br>
